2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1485,2016]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1845,1871]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Etymology</emphasis>
: After 
<emphasis box="[407,475,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">notios</emphasis>
southern, Gk, and 
<emphasis box="[686,739,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">chen</emphasis>
, from 
<taxonomicName box="[813,919,1845,1871]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Chenopis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,919,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Chenopis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the endemic subgenus of goose-like swans of Australasia, feminine, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Worthy &amp; Scofield &amp; Hand &amp; De Pietri &amp; Archer" authorityYear="2022" box="[451,655,1881,1907]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Notochen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bannockburnensis">
<emphasis box="[451,655,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">bannockburnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for ‘of the Bannockburn, alluding to its source from the Bannockburn Formation’. Suggested common name Bannockburn swan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1485,2016]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,1953,1979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Measurements</emphasis>
(mm): Preserved length 114, depth dorsal condyle 13.2, shaft width just proximal to fossa brachialis 17.0, shaft where not crushed 
<quantity box="[602,681,1989,2016]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" unit="mm" value="27.0">27 mm</quantity>
proximal to fossa brachialis 13.5 wide by 11.7 deep, diameter from pits for the origin of musculus flexor carpi ulnaris and origin of musculus supinator to the ventral side of tuberculum supracondylare ventrale at its mid-length 23.3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,433,222,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Referred specimens</emphasis>
: NMNZ 
<accessionNumber box="[536,624,222,249]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/S50823" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">S50823</accessionNumber>
, 
<accessionNumber box="[635,724,222,249]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/S50824" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">S50824</accessionNumber>
, two omal parts left coracoid, Bed HH1b [not Bed HH1a, contra 
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P." box="[151,370,259,285]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="97 - 114" refId="ref11124" refString="Worthy, T. H., Tennyson, A. J. D., Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P. (2008) A new species of the diving duck Manuherikia and evidence for geese (Aves: Anatidae: Anserinae) in the St Bathans Fauna (Early Miocene), New Zealand. Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand, 38 (2), 97 - 114. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014220809510549" type="journal article" year="2008">
Worthy 
<emphasis box="[244,302,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, wherein the bed was misidentified], Trench Excavation, 
<taxonomicName authority="River" authorityName="River" box="[1029,1244,259,285]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Manuherikia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Manuherikia River</taxonomicName>
Section; NMNZ 
<accessionNumber box="[151,240,294,321]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/S53149" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">S53149</accessionNumber>
, omal part R coracoid, Bed HH1b, Trench Excavation, 
<taxonomicName authority="River" authorityName="River" box="[869,1082,295,321]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Manuherikia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Manuherikia River</taxonomicName>
Section. All are from the basal 
<quantity box="[151,209,330,357]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" unit="m" value="25.0">25 m</quantity>
of the Bannockburn Formation in the 
<taxonomicName box="[642,908,331,357]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Manuherikia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lacustrina">
<emphasis box="[642,908,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Manuherikia lacustrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
biostratigraphic zone (
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Scofield, R. P. &amp; Salisbury, S. W. &amp; Hand, S. J. &amp; De Pietri, V. L. &amp; Blokland, J. C. &amp; Archer, M." box="[1166,1381,331,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="87 - 107" refId="ref10921" refString="Worthy, T. H., Scofield, R. P., Salisbury, S. W., Hand, S. J., De Pietri, V. L., Blokland, J. C. &amp; Archer, M. (2022) A new species of Manuherikia (Aves: Anatidae) provides evidence of faunal turnover in the St Bathans Fauna, New Zealand. Geobios, 70, 87 - 107. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. geobios. 2021.08.002" type="journal article" year="2022">
Worthy 
<emphasis box="[1259,1316,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
) and part of the St Bathans Fauna (
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P." box="[488,705,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="97 - 114" refId="ref11124" refString="Worthy, T. H., Tennyson, A. J. D., Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P. (2008) A new species of the diving duck Manuherikia and evidence for geese (Aves: Anatidae: Anserinae) in the St Bathans Fauna (Early Miocene), New Zealand. Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand, 38 (2), 97 - 114. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014220809510549" type="journal article" year="2008">
Worthy 
<emphasis box="[581,638,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schwarzhans, W. &amp; Scofield, R. P. &amp; Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Worthy, J. P. &amp; Worthy, T. H." box="[717,998,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="319 - 350" refId="ref10218" refString="Schwarzhans, W., Scofield, R. P., Tennyson, A. J. D., Worthy, J. P. &amp; Worthy, T. H. (2012) Fish remains, mostly otoliths, from the non-marine Early Miocene of Otago, New Zealand. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 57 (2), 319 - 350. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2010.0127" type="journal article" year="2012">
Schwarzhans 
<emphasis box="[873,930,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
). As described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P." box="[1199,1432,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="97 - 114" refId="ref11124" refString="Worthy, T. H., Tennyson, A. J. D., Hand, S. J. &amp; Scofield, R. P. (2008) A new species of the diving duck Manuherikia and evidence for geese (Aves: Anatidae: Anserinae) in the St Bathans Fauna (Early Miocene), New Zealand. Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand, 38 (2), 97 - 114. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014220809510549" type="journal article" year="2008">
Worthy 
<emphasis box="[1290,1347,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
(2008)
</bibRefCitation>
, these coracoids are very fragmentary: they feature a short broad facies articularis humeralis, a dorsoventrally broad base to the processus acrocoracoideus where it extends from the facies articularis humeralis, dorsal part sulcus supracoracoideus lacking pneumatic foramina, and a deep cup-like cotyla scapularis. Therefore, the structure of the processus procoracoideus and all parts more sternal are unknown and so these specimens do not afford any insights on relationships.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
Tentatively referred is CM Av40461, a proximal part of the right shaft of a humerus, collected 9-Jan-08, from Bed HH1a, 
<taxonomicName authority="River." authorityName="River." box="[285,504,619,645]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Manuherikia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Manuherikia River.</taxonomicName>
The width of the shaft at the distalmost edge is 
<quantity box="[1043,1143,619,645]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.24" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="12.4">12.4 mm</quantity>
and the width is 
<quantity box="[1336,1437,619,645]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.47" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="14.7">14.7 mm</quantity>
at the distal end of the crista deltopectoralis. Of appropriate size for CM 2017.37.919, it shows that the distal end of musculus latissimus dorsi abuts the crista deltopectoralis and that caudally the margo caudalis is compressed forming a rounded acute capital shaft ridge, as it does in species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latham" authorityYear="1802" box="[905,1016,727,753]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cereopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[905,1016,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cereopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechstein" authorityYear="1803" box="[1071,1155,727,753]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1071,1155,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,763,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Worthy &amp; Scofield &amp; Hand &amp; De Pietri &amp; Archer" authorityYear="2022" box="[324,643,763,789]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Notochen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bannockburnensis">
<emphasis box="[324,643,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Notochen bannockburnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be certainly referred to one or other of 
<taxonomicName box="[1174,1264,763,789]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Cygnini">Cygnini</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[1302,1401,763,789]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Anserini">Anserini</taxonomicName>
, as separation of these taxa on the distal humerus is principally by the distal projection of processus flexorius; it extends past the condylus ventralis in the 
<taxonomicName box="[526,622,835,861]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Anserini">Anserini</taxonomicName>
but it does not in the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Louchart et al. 2005)" baseAuthorityName="Louchart" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[867,1214,834,861]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Cygnini">
Cygnini (
<bibRefCitation author="Louchart, A. &amp; Vignaud, P. &amp; Likius, A. &amp; Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M." box="[972,1206,834,861]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="384 - 392" refId="ref9362" refString="Louchart, A., Vignaud, P., Likius, A., Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M. (2005) A new swan (Aves: Anatidae) in Africa, from the latest Miocene of Chad and Libya. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 25 (2), 384 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.1671 / 0272 - 4634 (2005) 025 [0384: ANSAAI] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2005">
Louchart 
<emphasis box="[1082,1139,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and this part of the fossil is missing. However, the large size, with distal width similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[995,1164,871,897]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atratus">
<emphasis box="[995,1164,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnus atratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with a stouter shaft, suggests a referral to 
<taxonomicName box="[391,481,907,933]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Cygnini">Cygnini</taxonomicName>
is likely.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
No Oligo-Miocene anatids of similar size are known from 
<collectingCountry box="[846,949,943,969]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H." box="[962,1115,943,969]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="411 - 454" refId="ref10598" refString="Worthy, T. H. (2009) Descriptions and phylogenetic relationships of two new genera and four new species of Oligo-Miocene waterfowl (Aves: Anatidae) from Australia. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 156, 411 - 454. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2008.00483. x" type="journal article" year="2009">Worthy 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Given the age disparity and geographic separation it is not likely that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Worthy &amp; Scofield &amp; Hand &amp; De Pietri &amp; Archer" authorityYear="2022" box="[615,934,979,1005]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Notochen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bannockburnensis">
<emphasis box="[615,934,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Notochen bannockburnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could relate to the few European Oligoceneearly Miocene putative anserines, but where taxa are comparable, differences exist. 
<taxonomicName authority="Aslanova &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, 1968" authorityName="Aslanova &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz" authorityYear="1968" class="Aves" family="Anseriformes (awaiting allocation)" genus="Guguschia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nailiae">
<emphasis box="[1114,1323,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Guguschia nailiae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Aslanova, S. M. &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, N. I." pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="325 - 338" refId="ref8004" refString="Aslanova, S. M. &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, N. I. (1968) A fossil swan from the Maykopian series of Azerbaydzhan. Acta Zoologica Cracovensis, 13 (14), 325 - 338." type="journal article" year="1968">Aslanova &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is a swan-sized anseriform of late Oligocene-early Miocene age that differs by an absence of a facet on the tuberculum supracondylare ventrale and a larger tuberculum supracondylare dorsale (
<bibRefCitation author="Aslanova, S. M. &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, N. I." box="[159,626,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="325 - 338" refId="ref8004" refString="Aslanova, S. M. &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz, N. I. (1968) A fossil swan from the Maykopian series of Azerbaydzhan. Acta Zoologica Cracovensis, 13 (14), 325 - 338." type="journal article" year="1968">Aslanova &amp; Burczak-Abramowicz 1968</bibRefCitation>
). Both 
<taxonomicName authority="(van Beneden, 1883)" baseAuthorityName="van Beneden" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[714,1189,1123,1149]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[714,938,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnopterus affinis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="van Beneden, P. J." box="[956,1181,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="132 - 134" refId="ref10511" refString="van Beneden, P. J. (1883) Sur quelques formes nouvelles des terrains du pays. Bulletin del'Academie des Sciences, Lettres et Beaux-Arts de Belgique, Series 3, 6, 132 - 134." type="journal article" year="1883">van Beneden, 1883</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
of middle Oligocene age and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kessler &amp; Hir, 2009" authorityName="Kessler &amp; Hir" authorityYear="2009" box="[244,776,1159,1185]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="neogradensis">
<emphasis box="[244,543,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnopterus neogradensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kessler, E. &amp; Hir, J." box="[551,776,1159,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="97 - 101" refId="ref8853" refString="Kessler, E. &amp; Hir, J. (2009) A new anserid species from the Neogene of Hungary. Fragmenta Palaeontologica Hungarica, 27, 97 - 101." type="journal article" year="2009">Kessler &amp; Hír, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
of middle Miocene age, have a proximodistally short facet for the attachment of the anterior articular ligament, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Lambrecht, K." box="[788,984,1195,1221]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref9193" refString="Lambrecht, K. (1931) Cygnopterus und Cygnavus, zwei fossile Schwane aus dem Tertiar Europas. Bulletin du Musee royal d'Histoire naturelle de Belgique, 7 (31), 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1931">Lambrecht (1931</bibRefCitation>
, Taf. II, 1, 2) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Kessler, E. &amp; Hir, J." box="[1189,1433,1195,1221]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="97 - 101" refId="ref8853" refString="Kessler, E. &amp; Hir, J. (2009) A new anserid species from the Neogene of Hungary. Fragmenta Palaeontologica Hungarica, 27, 97 - 101." type="journal article" year="2009">Kessler &amp; Hír (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. The known material of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lambrecht, 1931" authorityName="Lambrecht" authorityYear="1931" box="[428,902,1231,1257]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnavus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="senckenbergi">
<emphasis box="[428,695,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnavus senckenbergi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lambrecht, K." box="[705,902,1231,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref9193" refString="Lambrecht, K. (1931) Cygnopterus und Cygnavus, zwei fossile Schwane aus dem Tertiar Europas. Bulletin du Musee royal d'Histoire naturelle de Belgique, 7 (31), 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1931">Lambrecht, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the early Miocene, 
<typeStatus box="[1209,1312,1231,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">lectotype</typeStatus>
left femur and a distal tibiotarsus and phalanx, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kurochkin, 1968" authorityName="Kurochkin" authorityYear="1968" box="[617,1042,1267,1293]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnavus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[617,839,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnavus formosus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kurochkin, E. N." box="[847,1042,1267,1293]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="37 - 51" refId="ref9166" refString="Kurochkin, E. N. (1968) New Oligocene birds from Kazakhstan. Paleontological Journal, 2 (1), 37 - 51." type="journal article" year="1968">Kurochkin, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, early Oligocene, a tibiotarsus, are incomparable. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cheneval, 1984" authorityName="Cheneval" authorityYear="1984" box="[318,750,1303,1329]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alphonsi">
<emphasis box="[318,564,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnopterus alphonsi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cheneval, J." box="[572,750,1303,1329]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="33 - 115" refId="ref8276" refString="Cheneval, J. (1984) Les oiseaux aquatiques (Gaviiformes a Anseriformes) du gisement aquitanien de Saint-Gerand-le-Puy (Allier, France): Revision systematique. Palaeovertebrata, 14, 33 - 115." type="journal article" year="1984">Cheneval, 1984</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, synonymised with 
<taxonomicName authority="Lambrecht, 1931" authorityName="Lambrecht" authorityYear="1931" box="[973,1436,1303,1329]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Cygnavus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="senckenbergi">
<emphasis box="[973,1238,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Cygnavus senckenbergi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lambrecht, K." box="[1245,1436,1303,1329]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref9193" refString="Lambrecht, K. (1931) Cygnopterus und Cygnavus, zwei fossile Schwane aus dem Tertiar Europas. Bulletin du Musee royal d'Histoire naturelle de Belgique, 7 (31), 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1931">Lambrecht, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mlikovsky, J." box="[189,397,1339,1365]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" refId="ref9718" refString="Mlikovsky, J. (2002) Cenozoic Birds of the World. Part 1. Europe. Ninox Press, Praha, 407 pp." type="book" year="2002">Mlíkovský (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, has a worn humerus referred to it, however the details of the tuberculum supracondylare ventrale are not discernible in the publication (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheneval, J." box="[673,847,1375,1401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="33 - 115" refId="ref8276" refString="Cheneval, J. (1984) Les oiseaux aquatiques (Gaviiformes a Anseriformes) du gisement aquitanien de Saint-Gerand-le-Puy (Allier, France): Revision systematique. Palaeovertebrata, 14, 33 - 115." type="journal article" year="1984">Cheneval 1984</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
All similar-sized anserines of middle–late Miocene are placed in modern genera. The exception is the late Miocene-Pliocene 
<taxonomicName authority="Louchart, Vignaud, Likius, Mackaye &amp; Brunet, 2005" authorityName="Louchart, Vignaud, Likius, Mackaye &amp; Brunet" authorityYear="2005" box="[362,1216,1446,1473]" class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Afrocygnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chauvireae">
<emphasis box="[362,618,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Afrocygnus chauvireae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Louchart, A. &amp; Vignaud, P. &amp; Likius, A. &amp; Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M." box="[625,1216,1446,1473]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="384 - 392" refId="ref9362" refString="Louchart, A., Vignaud, P., Likius, A., Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M. (2005) A new swan (Aves: Anatidae) in Africa, from the latest Miocene of Chad and Libya. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 25 (2), 384 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.1671 / 0272 - 4634 (2005) 025 [0384: ANSAAI] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2005">Louchart, Vignaud, Likius, Mackaye &amp; Brunet, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Africa, which has a similarly distally robust shaft and differs by the scar for the attachment anterior articular ligament being rather circular instead of proximodistally elongate as in the fossil (
<bibRefCitation author="Louchart, A. &amp; Vignaud, P. &amp; Likius, A. &amp; Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M." box="[822,1056,1518,1545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" pagination="384 - 392" refId="ref9362" refString="Louchart, A., Vignaud, P., Likius, A., Mackaye, H. T. &amp; Brunet, M. (2005) A new swan (Aves: Anatidae) in Africa, from the latest Miocene of Chad and Libya. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 25 (2), 384 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.1671 / 0272 - 4634 (2005) 025 [0384: ANSAAI] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2005">
Louchart 
<emphasis box="[932,988,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">et al.</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
